com.codename1.rad.models

Class EntityType

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.codename1.rad.models.EntityType
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    EntityFactory, Iterable<Property>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DynamicEntityType, UI

    public class EntityType
extends Object
implements Iterable<Property>, EntityFactory

    Encapsulates an entity "type" for an Entity class. This is sort of like a "meta-class" that provides run-time support for data conversion, property lookup, and property binding. An EntityType should create its Propertys in its instance initializer. Typically, the entity type is declared as a static final anonymous class inside the Entity class definition as follows:

    public class UserProfile extends Entity {
   public static StringProperty name, description; (1)
   public static final EntityType TYPE = new EntityType(){{ (2)
       name = string(); (3)
       description = string();
   }};
   {
       setEntityType(TYPE); (4)
   }
}

    1. We define 2 properties of type StringProperty on the class. A StringProperty is simply a property that contains a String. These are defined public static so that we can access them conveniently from anywhere.

    2. We define an EntityType for the class. This is also public static because it is class-level (all objects of this class should share the same entity type).

    3. We create name and description properties on this entity type. Notice that this code runs in the instance intializer of the EntityType (the {{ and }} braces are not a typo). Running this code inside the instance initializer will ensure that the properties are added to the `EntityType’s property index.

    4. Inside the UserProfile instance initializer, we set the entity type to the entity type that we created above.

    Technically, you don’t need to provide direct property access to your entity properties at all. In our above UserProfile class we retained explicit references to the name and description properties, but we could have simply omitted this. I.e. The following is also a perfectly valid entity type definition:

    An entity type that doesn’t retain explicit references to its properties. The properties can still be accessed via their assigned tags.
    public class UserProfile extends Entity {
   public static final EntityType TYPE = new EntityType(){{
       string(tags(Thing.name));
       string(tags(Thing.description));
   }};
   {
       setEntityType(TYPE);
   }
}

    Property Types

    EntityType includes convenience methods for creating the standard property types:

    1. #string(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​)

    2. #Integer(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​)

    3. #Boolean(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​)

    4. #Double(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​)

    5. #date(com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​)

    6. entity(Class, Attribute[]) - an entity

    7. #list(java.lang.Class, com.codename1.rad.models.Attribute…​) - A list of entities.

    These methods will create the corresponding property and add it to the EntityType using addProperty(com.codename1.rad.models.Property). You can also create custom property types by subclassing AbstractProperty

        public static <T extends Entity> void register(Class<T> cls,
                                               EntityType et,
                                               EntityFactory factory)

        Register an entity class and its optional factory. This should be called before using an Entity class.

        Type Parameters:
        T -
        Parameters:
        cls - The entity class to register.
        factory - The optional factory to create instances of this class. If the class is public and has a no-arg constructor, then a factory isn’t necessary. But if it is private or doesn’t have a public no-arg constructor you should provide a factory.

      • isDynamic

        public boolean isDynamic()

        Flag indicating whether this is a dynamic entity type. Dynamic entity types are types that have no specified schema (you can add any properties, to entities of this type, without being constrained by the properties defined in the EntityType.

        Entities that don’t have a type specified with Entity.setEntityType(com.codename1.rad.models.EntityType) will, by default have a dynamic entity type.
